0 varieties. Worth $1.25 5\neaeh. g\nSPECIAL, 75c Each.\nAbout 50 varieties. Worth $1.00\neach. g\nI SPECIAL, 50c Each.\nVlartim Co., I\n:hina. Glass, Silver, Etc., H\nmid 1214=118 G St.\n4\nIIA RAILROAD\n5TER TOUR\nTO\n1\nE W ROUND TRIP\niPE $13.50\nA%jr from Washington\nY\n'<1 for re-turn passage- until Aprtl inclui?-r\ndays' board (from dinner Saturbreakfast\nMonday morning) at\nSAPE MAY\nWARE RIVER BRIDGE ROUTE\nr Cape May direct at 12:20 noon\nAND STANDARD COACHES\nmade and tickets procured upon applieaI).,\nFifteenth and (J Sts.. Washington, I\nGEO. W. BOYD\nGeneral Passenger Agent\nNIGHT TARGET WORK\nSpectacular Feature of Magdalena\nBay Firing.\nAIR ALIVE WITH METEORS\n\"Tracers\" Leave a Trail of Fire Behind\nThem.\nREPELLING TORPEDO ATTACKS\n\nGun Crews Working in Glare of Reflectors?Search\nLights Make\na Gorgeous Display.\nMAGDALENA BAY. March 31.?The\nnight firing by the battleships of the Atlantic\nfleet is a brilliant spectacle. It is\nthe perfection of pyrotechnics. The\nsweeping of the great shafts of light from\nthe searchlights, the bursting flashes of\nfire from the gun muzzles, the sparkstrewn\npathways of the soaring and flaming\nshells, the ricochets that resemble\ngiant skyrockets and the tremendous\nechoes of bellowing sounds that come\nacross the waters and over the silent,\nfog-enshrouded hills combine to present\na scene that thrills long after the firing\nhas ceased.\nIt is the work of repelling attacks of\nan enemy's imaginary torpedo thrust.\nBlack targets with white centers are the\nobjects at which the ships are directing\ntheir fire. Two or three ships may be seen\nfiring at a time. Big searchlights of intense\nbrilliancy and power of penetration,\nhigh up in the fighting tops of toe mainmast\nand foremast, turn upon the targets\nlong before the ship comes upon the\nfiring radius.\nFloating Fairyland.\nThe lights of the ship are all blazing\nout. Every porthole is a white light,\nstanding out in the inky darkness. Other\nlights hang here and there on the luted\ngangways and other necessary locations.\nThe ensemble is of irregular outline,\nbearing no resemblance to the lines ot a\nbattleship. The red and white signal\nlights strung up the halyards of. the foremast\nare alternating in their colored\nflashes transmitting official messages to\nother ships. Heavy clusters of electric\nlights are on the forward and after\nbridges, the big reflectors turned sharply\ndownward ten feet distant, where they\nilluminate like day the breaches of the\ngun8. The gun crew wor.is in perfect\nlight, as though the sun were shining.\nThe ship steams on the range at a rapid\nspeed, her powerful searchlights hung out\nthis way and that. Soon It passes a red\nburning signal light. It is the \"standby\"\nsignal. The searchlights are now concentrated\nupon the targets, tiny spots far off\nthe port bow.\nFlight of the Shells.\nA whistle is blown, an officer shouts the\nsharp command \"Fire!\" The three-pounders\nand three-inch guns go Instantly Into\naction. The exploding powder flashes out\nfrom the muzzle in a puff of flame, and\nthe projectile leaps away towara the target.\nIt traverses the Intervening distance\nin an inBtant.\nBy means of what is known as the\n\"night tracer\" the flight of the shell is\nfollowed with the naked eyes. It is a\nstream of Are that shows in the wake of\nthe shell. Its operation is a strictly military\n.secret. The height which the leaping\nshell attains is almost incredible. It\nmust sometimes be 500 feet.\nIt is estimated by an officer prominent\nin the fleet that at target practice more\nthan sixty-four tons of ammunition has\nbeen shot away. It costs $S7 for the shell\nand $110 for the powder to Are a single\n12-ineh shell. The total cost for flrlng\npractice of a ship like those in the flrst\nand second divisions is estimated at $17.000.\nor a total for the eight battleships of\n$136,000.\nADMIRAL EVANS' CONDITION.\nHe Will Proceed to Washington\nAfter a Short Rest.\nMAGDALEN A BAY. March 31.-The\nwork of target practice by the fleet is\nnow two-thirds tinlshed. While it has\nbeen satisfactory in the main the scores\nof none of the ships or guns have been\ngiven out. All such publication must\nhome from the Navy Department.\nAdmiral Evans' health is Improving,\nslowly. His sole reason for asking that\nhe be relieved of his command is that\nhe gains strength slowly. The attack of\nrheumatism, to which he has been subject\nfor many years, was severe, and It\nhas left him in a weak condition. Nevertheless.\neven when he was in pain he\nattended to his duties. Twice while at\nRio de Janeiro he was flat on his back,\nyet he dictated correspondence, signed\npapers and gave directions about the\nfleet. Everything was reported to him\nduring the cruise, and he ordered every\nmove that was made. He went over the\ncharts of the Strait of Magellan inch by\ninch personally, and during the passage\nof that waterway he took personal\ncharge of the fleet. Everything was\ndone under his direction. He feels that\nhe cannot gain strength at sea as he\ncould on land. He will take the fleet\nto San Francisco a!nd tliere haul down\nhis flag. After a short rest he will\nproofed to Washington. His son, Lieut.\nEvans of the Louisiana, will go .with\nhim hut will return to his shio. Ad\nmiral E^vans ts able to sit on his bridge\nfor several hours each day. and he has\nalso been on the quarterdeck. He remained\non the Connecticut while the\nflagship was engaged In target practice.\nNo 111 results followed the noise and concussion.\nCapt. Jngersoll. chief of staff, and Lieut.\nCommander Chandler, flag secretary, will\nalso go cast from San Francisco.\nThe fleet is now shaken down Into a\nunit Valuable data have been secured\nas to cruising radius and engineering\nstrength. The ships are in much better\ncondition than when they started from\nHampton roads Practically every ship\nIs able to make its own repairs. If\nnecessary, the entire fleet could steam\naround the world without docking or going\nto any navy yard for minor repairs.\nAll the officers are delighted with the\nshowing made.\nSUTLERS ARE SORE\nBAD BUSINESS OUTLOOK AT\nMAGDALENA BAT.\nBy Associated Press.\nMAGDALENA BAY, March 21, via San\nDiego. Cal.. March 31.?The four enterprising\nbusiness firms who set up their\n11) tie stands along the shore in front of\nthe town are meeting with a depressing\nlull in trade with tne neet. ine sailors\nare not allowed ashore except now and\nthen a squad In charge of an officer for\nsome particular purpose, so that the much\nexpected flow of^trade is languishing. The\nhot sands along the beach are denuded\nof prospective customers and the Impromptu\nmerchants are not all sanguine\nof the financial feature of their ventures.\nTheir little shacks set along near the pier\nwere constructed of pieces of canvas or\nrudely arranged boards. The weather is\nwarm, day and night, and little shelter is\nrequired. Large stores of tobacco, fruits,\nstationery supplies and liquors are\nstacked within.\nTwo men from San Francisco, Sullivan\nand Whitney, landed here from Mazatlan\ntwo weeks in advance of the fleet with a\nmiscellaneous cargo, including sixty cases\nof beer and forty of whisky. They had\npaid the Mexican duties on all of it. For\ndays the local official refused to allow\ni i horn to land it. Then they were permitted\nto bring It ashore and the sale of the beverages\nwas strictly forbidden.\nHave Booze to Barn.\n\"We can't do anything with It but drink\nIt up ourselves,\" said one of the proprietors.\nOne of them has another large supply\ncoming soon from San Francisco on\na sailing vessel, which shipment he had\nordered before he knew of the embargo.\nHe will store it away with the other contraband\nwhen it arrives. Large shipments\nof Mexican oranges from somewhere on\nthe southern end of the peninsula have\nbeen brought in by boats four days from\nMagdalena and are finding a ready sale\nat good prices. Fresh fruit Is a luxurygreat\nl'y esteemed by the officers and men.\nMost of the merchants came from Mexico\nCity, and their stocks of goods came byrail\nto the western coast. Many of them\nhave been with the fleet before In the j\ncapacity of shore caterers, but their ex-\ni perience at Magdalena bay is something\n1 of a new one.\nThe Mexican customs officer is keenly\nalert In his business. Lues, the bumboat\nman from the Atlantic coast, narrowly escaped\nserious difficulty with the authorities\nwhen he attempted to barter- his\ngoods in the bay without paying the required\ncustoms duties. Only a diplomatic\nletter to the authorities from Admiral\nEvans saved the merchantman from serious\nconsequences. Others who come here\nin similar quest are not likely to fare so\nlightly, according to the statement of the\nMexican officer.\nCHANGE IN EXCISE LAW.\nDistrict Commissioners Unable to\nAgree Upon a Measure.\nAfter several weeks of consideration of\nthe various bills introduced during the\npresent session of Congress affecting the\nexcise laws of the District, several of\nwhich provide for prohibition in the District,\nthe Commissioners have been unable'\nto come to an agreement. The\nbills have been referred to them for a\nreport upon their merits, but as each of\nthe three \"Commissioners lias a different\nview upon the question it is said to be\nlikely that several weeks will elapse before\nthey finally report to Congress.\nOne of the Commissioners is said to\nfavor legislation prohibiting the licensing\nof any saloon located within 1.000 feet of\na place of worship. The present provision\nin this respect places the limitation at 400\nfeet of a place of worship. The captains\nof the various police precincts throughout\nthe city were busily engaged last week\nmeasuring the distances between saloons\nand churches, with respect to the proposed\n1.000-feet provision, and it is said\nthat from information furnished by these\ncaptains such a limitation would wipe out\n33 of the 317 saloons now operating with a\nlicense.\nAnother form of legislation affecting the\nlocal excise laws is one which provides\nfor Increasing the license tax from $$00 a\nyear to $1,600. It will be necessary for\nthe Commissioners to hold several more\nconferences npon 'this subject before they\ncan reach an agreement, it was said today.\nand it is also stated authoritatively\nthat when the Commissioners do report\nto Congress their report will not be in\nfavor of absolute prohibition.\ni\nAPPEAL TO THE SENATE.\n-n\nCommissioners Hope for More Liberal\nAppropriations.\nLittle surprise is expressed by the Com- cj\nmissioners at the big: cut in their annual\nestimates made by the House committee\non appropriations. Although the Commissioners\nrefuse to discuss the matter.\nit is understood they will press before\nthn Senate the estimates not granted by rr\nthe House, and they hope for success\nin\nin the end.\nac\nAs the printed records of the confer- f<1\nences between the Commissioners and the j\"L\ncommittee on appropriations show that ar\nthe former told the committee that the so\nDistrict revenues were ample to meet all ch\ntheir estimates; that the estimates asked 1\nfor were all necessary, and not made to ar\nbe subjected to cutting, and that they tic\nshould not in justice be cut. so as to wi\nmake the District pay a disproportionate T.\namount on the advances received from to\nthe United States Treasury on account D\nof extraordinary projects of improve- er\nments in the District. Tire committee ds\nreport leaves a million dollars of District 1\nrevenues unappropriated, and. of course, hi\nif it had been appropriated another mil- ar\nlion from the national revenues would ci\nhave been added to it, making two mil- si\nliona additional appropriations. dc\nThis $1,000,000 of district revenues, the sp\ncommittee report says, is to be applied to\nto the repayment of advances from the I df\nTreasury Department. Such an amount,\nthe Commissioners said in their argument to\nbefore the committee, would be at least pi\ntwice as great as would be reasonable Fi\nin any one year, and would compel the til\ncutting out of extraordinary projects of\nimprovement and the cutting down of pc\ncurrent needs of all the municipal serv- w\nInAO Thfi f'om m i foirttint-n\nivvv viiiitiipoivuci o aatvru llic U111~ vr\nmittee 10 differentiate between their es- lit\ntlmates for extraordinary projects of im- sa\nprovement. amounting to $3,291,350. in- Pi\neluding ll.93tt.00l) for public school build- of\nings and grounds. made necessary by pf\nthe fact that Congress had cjut $2.3pO.?H)0 j to\nin the past ten years out of the Com- nr\nmissioners' estimates for public school te\nbuildings and grounds, and their esti- 1 R\ni >ates for current expenditures, amounting M\nto $0,400,000, and $975,000 for sinking gi\nfund and interest on the old bonded debt, til\nThey asked the committee to provide for th\nthe extraordinary appropriations, cover-\ning besides the public school buildings,\nhigh-pressure fire service, suburban and\ntrunk sewers, railway terminal work,\nchronic municipal, by charging them to js\na capital account covered by advances i\nfrom the Treasury, to lie repaid with 1S_\nformer advances in reasonable annual ps\nrepayments. This would enable the Dis- m\ntriet to carry its share of all the ap- a*\npropr'.ations, so that all the estimates\nmight be allowed without inconvenience M\nand without delaying the progress of\nthe city or imperiling its safety from d?\ndisease, fire or crime.\nth\nDEFENSE OF LUNDY.\nOU\nStatement Made Today by Attorney ur\nJohn H. Wilson. J?\nJohn H. Wilson, attorney for Louis ui\nLundy, the colored man who was shot\nFriday night by Representative J. Thomas\nHeflln of Alabama while on a Pennsyl- p,\nvanla avenue car. said today in an Inter- on\nview with a Star reporter: to'\n\"While The Star has been admirably\nfair In Its reports and editorials in the sj,\nLundy case, as counsel for Lundy I deem en\nit expedient at this time to call attention d*\nto a few reports now current that might\nprejudicially affect public sentiment.\n\"First. Lundy has not been convicted re\nof criminal offenses or any other offenses th\ntwelve times, as reported. As a matter ar\nof fact and of record he has not been con- at\nvlcted half that number of times. And m\nfurther, a statement was published, in\nsubstance, that the colored attorneys of\nthe District of Columbia were interested\nin the case only as a racial issue?none of lie\nthem having offered bond or collateral for w|\nDundy's appearance. In this connection Wj\nI wish to call attention to the fact that pa\nsince Dundy was charged with no crim- p\ninal offense whatever, bond or collateral p,\nwas quite unnecessary 1 hence the inac- W]\ncuracy of the statement. The facts in the in\ncase will be withheld at present. th\n\"Attorney D. M. King is associated with lie\nme in the Interest ofgDtindy. The Colored en\nCivil and Political league of America, of ha\nwhich Rev. Dr. S. L. Corrothers is presi- na\ndent and Rev. Dr. George W. Do? vice la\npresident, has retained the law tirm of ar\nHughes Gray to assist me. tii\n\"Rev. S. D. Corrothers has expressed in no\nno uncertain terms his determination to ha\nsee that Dundy's rights are protected.\" ye\nof\np? 1 ha\n1 re\nCO\nSave money and health,\nby cutting out improper p?\nfood. Try\nISt\nml\nfoflifMLMimlte I\nVUaUjJJALTiLNiyiLO ft\nSe\n\"There's a Reason\" iu\nre\nwl\n'-j se\n^^tPers\nF [/ffl Personal knowledj\njiJJflr this competitive age an\n(^jjr P03368501^ l^e ^ronl r\nIMfflj A vast fund of personal\nhighest excellence in any field\nIN A Knowledge of F<\nJr edge of Products are all\nj[j when a true and wholesome r\n1ff ot h igs and blixir or Oenna,\nU ethical product which has met\nM gives universal satisfaction, bee\nKnown Quality, Ki\nIA Parts and has won the valua\naa world, who know of their own\n|l and best of family laxatives, foi\nThis valuable remedy h\n\\l under the name of?Syrup o\nwide acceptance as the most\nlaxative principles, obtained frc\nJfi and the Well Informed\nadopted the more elabc\nElixir of Senna? a\nbut doubtless it wi\nname of?Syrup\nname of t!\nDVAAT AfTTAnXTQ TAPT\nit xiia nunuiLu xxxx x\n&.NDIDACY WOULD FALL BUT\nFOR THE ADMINISTRATION.\nKANSAS CITY. Mo.. March 31.?Demoats\nfrom all parts of Missouri to the\nimber of 2,bort attended a dollar banquet\nConvention Hall last night, under the\nispiees of the Young Men's Democratic\nub of M issouri. William J. Bryan and\nidson Harmon were the guests of honor\nid principal speakers. Some 15.000 perns\nthronged the hall as auditors and\nleered the speakers.\nDemocratic clubs In St. Louis. St. Joseph\nid other cities of the state sent delega)ns\nto the dinner. Among the guests\nere four former governors of Missouri?\nT. Crittenden. David R. Frawcis. Senar\nWilliam J. Stone and Alexander M.\nockery?as also was the present govnor.\nJoseph W. Folk. All of the candiites\nfor state offices were present.\nMr. Bryan's opening statement, that \"we\nive met to begin the campaign of 1 tv\nid to present those principles and polies\nwhich ought to appeal to p ogresve\nrepublicans as well as to traditional\n'moerats,\" was the keynote of his\nleech- In giving his approval of Senar\nLa Follette as the republican candiite\nfor President. Mr. Bryan said:\n\"If the President had picked out Senar\nLa Follette. a real reformer; if the relblican\nparty had rallied to Senator La\nollette s support, it could have compelled\ne confidence of reform republicans.\"\nMr. Bryan said that without the supirt\nof the administration Secretary Taft\nmiM si^rpf-k- have a state ill the con\nntion. and with I lie President's support\nis having an uphill fight. Mr. Bryan\niid that Taft made thf best man the\nresident could find among his cabinet\nfleers, but that Secretary Taft's su'rlority\nover his colleagues was due' not\nhis positive virtues, but to the fact that\n>ne of the rest of them had any reform\nndencles whatever. Mr. Bryan said the\noosevelt sentiment was strong in tbe\nississippi and Missouri valleys, and arjed\nthat the democratic ticket was ended\nto the support of this sentiment in\ne coming campaign.\nRoosevelt Support Not Personal.\nSaid Mr. Bryan:\n\"It is only a recognition of a fact which\nbecoming clear to all to say that there\na democratic element in the republican\nirty to which a successful appeal can be\nade. In the tirst place, what is known\ni the Roosevelt sentiment is strong in\ne valleys of the Mississippi and tbe\nissouri; and the Roosevelt sentiment is\nit so much attachment to a person as\nvotion to an idea witl'i which the pern\nhas identified himself. And what is\nis idea? It is the idea that conditions\ne not what they should be. For years\ne democratic party 'has been pointing\nit the abuses which have been growing\nider republican rule, but those abus. s\nive been denied by republican lenders,\nid the country has been congratulated\n.on the possession of everything essenil\nto its welfare.\n\"To the surprise of democrats, and to\ne surprise of republicans as well, the\nesident after his election began to recumend\nremedial legislation, taking as\ns guide tlie platform declarations of the\nmocratic party. He did not follow in\ne footsteps of democracy out of any dere\nto compliment tbe democrats or to\ncourage them, but simply because tbe\nmocrats had pre-empted all the ground\nfront, and lie could not go forward\nithout trespassing upon their land.\n'Now. what prospect is there that the\npublican national convention will satisfy\ne urgent demands of reform republicis?\nI venture to predict that no serious\ntempt will be made to satisfy tihese deands.\nPresident Would Be Powerless.\n'If, in the coming campaign, the repubans\nhave an ambiguous platform, tilled\nIth glittering generalities and fragrant\nith Douqu.'ts tnrown at the republican\nrty, a republican President elected upon\nwould be as powerless as the present\nesident has been. I >>ay powerless?for\nliat has the President succeeded in dog?\nThere are more trusts today than\nere were when he entered the office, and\nhas never succeeded in getting a law\nacted to strengthen the present law. He\nis not succeeded in putting a trust magite\nin the penitentiary, and the only\nrge tine that has been imposed has\noused more criticism than eommenda>n\namong republican leaders. He lias\ni? v tariff rof/trm onH\nV ?V?. <vin? J Ul IgT\nis been in office for more than seven\nars. He has not secured the enactment\nthe necessary labor legislation. lie\nls not secured an income tax. and the\npublican senators forced him into a\nmpromise on the railroad question.\nBut even a good platform would be\njrthless without a candidate who emdied\nthe spirit of the platform. The\nesident has picked out Secretary Taft\nid gi ven him the support of the adminration.\nWithout the support of the adinistraiion\nthe Secretary would scarcely\nve a state in the convention, and witii\ne President's support he is having an\nihill fight. He lias no record as a reiorm.\nand his speeches do not indicate a\nlinite purpose or a courageous program,\np may Vie tlie best man tne President\nu!d find among his cabinet ifficers; but\ncretary's Taft's superiority over bis\nlleagites is due not to his positive vires.\nbut to the fact that none of the\nst of them have any reform tendencies\nliatever. In fact, the widespread reform\nntiment among the republican masses\nTHE V^iUE\nOF\n>onalKnowi\n;e is the winning factor in the culminating\nd when of ample character it places its\nanks of\nill Informed of the World.\noiowledge is really essential to the achieven\nof human effort.\nm _ 1\n>rms, Knowledge ot functions and\nof the utmost value and in questions of life\nemedy is desired it should be remembered\nmanufactured by the California Fig Syrup\nwith the approval of the most eminent phy\nause it is a remedy of\nnown Excellence and Known Co\nible patronage of millions of the Well Infon\npersonal knowledge 